"Abstract Last month I wrote that the impact of Sarbanes-Oxley and other legislation is starting to have its impact on organizations. This has been clearly reflected in many press reports on the high cost of compliance with Sarbanes-Oxley – not only the cost of documenting internal controls and compliance therewith, but the much increased audit fees for certifying the adequacy of the regime of internal controls. General Electric has complained that it was spending US $30 million on the internal control provisions of Sarbanes-Oxley. These increased costs would appear to be an indictment on the quality of audits or of poor internal control or of documentation."
